Add liquids to dry ingredients, whisking until smooth. Bake 35-40 minutes, or until done. Cool completely. Frost, if desired.
Place sausage, celery, onion, butter, chicken broth, salt, black pepper, sage in a large bowl. Cover and cook on low setting for 8 to 10 hours.
Mix all ingredients together and place them in a casserole dish. Cover with crushed potato chips and sprinkle with paprika. Bake uncovered at 350 degrees for 30 to 35 minutes or until hot and bubbly.

Heat oil in a large non-stick skillet over medium-high heat. Add broccoli florets, chunky peanut butter, vegetable stock, soy sauce, seasoned rice vinegar, oil, garlic cloves, dry crushed red pepper. Stir fry 3 minutes. Stir fry 5 minutes or until broccoli is cooked through.

Preheat oven to 350 degrees f. Coat a 2 quart casserole dish with nonstick cooking spray. Cook the macaroni according to package directions. Drain and place in a large bowl. Add the remaining ingredents except for the corn chips. Mix well then pour into a casserol dish and sprinkle with corn chips bake for 30-35 minutes, or until hot and bubbly, and the top is golden.

Place sausages, onion, bacon, french onion soup mix, water, frozen mixed vegetables, fresh parsley in crock pot. Pour soup, undiluted, over top. Bake uncovered 30 min at 350 f, or 6-8 hrs on low in crock pot.

Line a 9 x 13 pan with aluminum foil. Preheat oven to 400. Place saltine crackers in pan in rows. I usually can fit about 24 in the pan. In a saucepan, bring the butter and sugar to a boil. After it begins boiling, boil for 3 minutes. Immediately pour the butter-sugar mixture on the crackers. Bake in the oven for 7 minutes. Take out of the oven, pour chocolate chips over crackers, and smooth them out after they melt. Cool in the fridge until the chocolate has hardened. Cut into squares.
Heat oil in a large skillet or wok over medium high heat. Add chicken. Cook and stir until lightly browned. Add remaining ingredients. Cook and stir about 10 minutes. Serve.

Preheat oven to 350f. In a large mixing bowl, cream together the butter, sugars, eggs, vanilla, flour, baking soda, salt, baking powder, baking soda, semi-sweet chocolate chips. Combine the wet and dry ingredients. Stir in chocolate chips. With your fingers, place golf ball-sized dough portions 2-inches apart on an ungreased cookie sheet. Bake 9-10 minutes or just until edges are light brown.

In a plastic container with a lid, combine all ingredients. Seal and place in the freezer until frozen solid. Take out of freezer and let thaw. Drink when it has thawed and is slushy. Or put in blender and blend until slushy. Garnish with fresh cranberries, zest of a lime or an orange slice.

In a large microwave-safe bowl, combine sugar, water, cinnamon, pecan halves, dried orange pieces, butter, brown sugar, ground cinnamon, banana extract, rum extract, rum extract. Spread onto waxed paper to cool. Store in an airtight container.

Preheat a grill to medium. Cut four 12-inch-long sheets of heavy-duty foil. Drizzle 1 teaspoon olive oil into the center of each sheet. Season the chicken with salt and pepper. Lay 1 piece of chicken in the center of each sheet and spread 1 tablespoon pesto on top. Mound one-quarter of the zucchini, tomatoes and scallions over each chicken breast. Dollop 3 tablespoons pesto over each mound. Fold the foil over the chicken and vegetables. Pinch the edges to seal. Cover and grill the packets over indirect heat for 25 minutes. Remove from the grill and open carefully.
Place medley on top of grilled cheese and serve.

Place the pork tenderloin in a slow cooker. Pour the garlic over the pork. Cover and cook on low until well cooked and the pork shreds easily, 6 to 7 hours. Drain well. Stir in barbecue sauce. Serve over hamburger buns.

Combine all of the ingredients, except the pears, together in a blender. Cover and blend on low speed for 3 minutes. Pour into a greased 9-inch pie pan. Let stand about 5 minutes then sprinkle with pears. Bake at 350 degrees for 40 minutes. Serve warm or cool.

Preheat oven to 350 degrees f. Lightly grease 2 non-stick 12 hole mini muffin pans. Divide silver state brownies among holes. Stir butter and chocolate in small saucepan over low heat until smooth. Stir in sugar, cool to just warm. Stir in egg, then flour and cream. Spoon mixture into prepared pan. Press one rolo into centre of each quantity of mixture. Spread mixture so that rolo is completely enclosed. Bake in oven about 15 minutes. Using a sharp pointed knife, loosen sides of brownies from pan, stand 10 minutes. Remove brownies gently from pan.

Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease a large cookie sheet. Beat butter and sugar in a large bowl with mixer at high speed, until light and fluffy. Add egg and vanilla. Beat until well blended. Combine flour, cocoa, cream of tartar, baking soda and salt in a medium bowl. Add to butter mixture. Mix until uniform. Mix in chopped cherries. Drop dough by tablespoonfuls onto prepared cookie sheet. Bake about 10-12 minutes or until set.

Preheat oven to 350f. Add butter, sugar, dutch-processed cocoa powder, salt, baking powder, vanilla, eggs, all-purpose flour, chocolate chips and mix with a fork until just blended. Do not overmix. Pour into a silicone or buttered 9x9 pan. Bake for 20-25 minutes.

Place all ingredients in a food processor and blend until smooth. Chill at least a few hours before tasting. Can serve with chips, crackers, or as a veggie dip. Keeps well in fridge. Cooking time listed is for chilling time.

Place barcardi limon lemonade in a saucepan and bring to a boil. Cook until slightly tender. Pack in pint jars. Place a sliver of lemon and lime in each jar. Combine the oil, juices and garlic in a saucepan and bring to a boil. Pour immediately over the barcardi limon lemonade and seal. Place caps on jars. Process for 20 mins. In a water bath canner.
Combine the red currants, cherries, red currants, blueberries, strawberries, raspberries, blackberries, mint, and mix well. Serve immediately.

Place mangoes, orange juice, lime juice, club soda, ice cubes in blender until smooth, stopping to scrape down the sides. Add the ice and blend well, pour into glasses and garnish if desired. Serve immediately if possible, otherwise chill in the freezer for one hour, then refrigerate. When ready to enjoy, shake again or re-mix in blender, then serve.

Drop dough by tablespoonfuls onto prepared cookie sheet. Bake about 10-12 minutes or until set.

Pinch edges together to seal. Grill 7 to 9 minute on each side or until burgers are done. Spread buns with mayo mixture. Fill with lettuce, tomatoes, burgers and peppers.

Heat oven to 400 degrees. Grease round baking dish. Melt butter in skillet over med-lo heat. Add onion and red pepper, cook until soft. Add ham, cook 2 mins more. Beat eggs and milk in bowl. Stir in cheese and add veggies and ham. Season with salt and pepper. Transfer to prepared dish. Bake 20 minutes or until top is puffy and brown. Cut into wedges and serve warm.
Preheat oven to 350f. Cream together margarine, sugar, eggs, flour, cocoa powder, white chocolate chips. Pour mixture onto cookie sheet and spread. Bake for 20-25 minutes.

Heat olive oil in a large skillet over medium heat. Add garlic, shallot, crushed red pepper flakes, tomatoes, butternut squash, penne, fresh parsley and cook for about a minute. When squash is tender about 10 minutes for shreds, 15 or so for small cubes cook pasta until it is tender. Combine sauce and pasta, and serve, garnished with parsley or parmesan.

Preheat oven to 400f. Peel, core and slice apples into a bowl. Add brown sugar, cinnamon, water and salt. Mix well to coat apples. Place in two ramikins or small au gratin dishes, sprayed with cooking spray. Dot with butter and spread cheese over top. Bake for 20 to 30 minutes or until apples fall.

Preheat oven to 375f. Heat a little oil in frying pan and brown stew meat along with onions and carrots. Remove from pan. Layer sliced potatoes, onion, carrot and meat in a 3 pint casserole, finishing with a layer of potatoes. Pour over the stock. Brush the potatoes with 1 tbsp melted butter. Cover and bake for 1 hour. Remove the hot pot from the oven. Uncover and brush the potatoes again with melted butter or dripping. Return to the oven for a further 30 minutes, uncovered, to brown the potatoes. Serve garnished with parsley.

Add spaghetti, parmesan cheese, cream, parsley flakes, salt, and pepper, and mix well. Pour into a buttered 2 quart baking dish. Cover and bake at 325 degrees until it is warm, about 15 minutes. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease a 13 x 9-inch baking dish. In a large bowl using an electric mixer at medium speed cream the butter with both sugars and vanilla until no sugar granules remain. Add in the peanut butter and beat until combined. Add in eggs and beat until combined. In a bowl combine the flour with baking soda and oats. Add to the creamed mixture and mix on low speed until combined. Mix in chocolate chips. Transfer and spread into prepared baking dish. Bake for 22-25 minutes or until just set. Cool then cut into squares.

Preheat oven to 400. Lightly butter an ovenproof dish large enough to hold the apricot halves in a single layer. Arrange the apricots in the dish, cut side up. Sprinkle the apricots with the almonds and drizzle the honey over the top. Dust with the ginger. Bake for 12-15 minutes, until the apricots are tender and the almonds golden. Remove from the oven and serve at once, with ice cream on the side, if you want.

Heat the oil in a 9-inch saute pan over medium heat. Add the carrots and cook until lightly browned on all sides, about 3 minutes per side. Season with salt and pepper. Add the ginger, garlic, and shallots and cook over medium-low heat, stirring occasionally, until the shallots are softened, 5-7 minutes. Add the honey, orange juice, soy sauce and water. Cover with a round of waxed paper that fits snugly on the vegetables. Cook the carrots slowly on top of the stove, stirring occasionally, until the carrots are tender and the juices have formed a glaze, 30-40 minutes. Garnish with the mint.

Cook pasta according to directions on package, drain and cool by running cool water over it. Let drain thoroughly. Combine pasta with peppers, carrots and parsley. Add vinaigrette and mix well. Add feta cheese, mix lightly, lifting the pasta and cheese mixture until the cheese is distributed throughout. Chill for an hour before serving.

Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Brown beef and onions in skillet. Drain. Mix in tomato sauce, garlic and oregano. Place in a 2-quart casserole dish. Top with corn. Then spread mashed potatoes over the corn. Lay cheese over the mashed potatoes in a single layer. Bake for about 25-30 minutes or until the cheese is completely melted.

Preheat oven to 400 degrees f. Place the roasted red peppers on a foil-lined baking sheet. Toss with 1 tablespoon of olive oil and spread the peppers in a single layer. Place in the oven and bake until golden, about 30 minutes. Remove the roasted red peppers from the oven. Add the remaining ingredients to the roasted red peppers and carefully stir to coat all the peppers and nuts. Spread the mixture out to a single layer. Bake for 10 more minutes. Let cool slightly and place in serving bowls.
Combine all ingredients and mix well. Serve with crackers.

Mix flour tortillas, refried beans, lean ground beef, taco seasoning mix, water, cheddar cheese, taco sauce, onion, sour cream. Cover and cook on low for 3-4 hours or until the cheese is melted and mixture is well heated. Stir after 2 hours. Add in the onions, stir to combine. Serve with tortilla chips.

Preheat oven to 400f. Coat 12 cup muffin pan with non-stick cooking spray. Mix carrot, egg, cheese, and chives. Add flour and baking powder, stir. Spoon batter equally among muffin cups. Bake 25-30 minutes until golden brown.
Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Mix ingredients together in a large bowl until well-blended. Bake 12 minutes for chewy cookies. Bake 15 minutes for crisp.

To make the dressing, in a small bowl, combine the lemon juice and garlic. Slowly whisk in olive oil until the mixture is creamy. Season with salt and pepper. Place angel hair in a serving bowl and add dressing to taste. Mix well. Top with avocado slices, drizzle a bit more dressing over them and season with a pinch of salt. Using a vegetable peeler, shave slivers of parmesan over the top.

In a food processor puree the fish fillets with the shallot, the anchovies, lemon juice and the cayenne. With the motor running add the olive oil in a stream. Add the scotch and the butter cubes. Blend the mixture until it is combined well. Pack the mixture into small ramekins or a crock, and chill it, covered until it is firm, preferrably at least overnight. Garnish the potted kippers with the fresh dill.

Heat the oil in a 9-inch saute pan over medium heat. Add the carrots and cook until lightly browned on all sides, about 3 minutes per side. Season with salt and pepper. Add the ginger, garlic, and shallots and cook over medium-low heat, stirring occasionally, until the shallots are softened, 5-7 minutes. Add the honey, orange juice, soy sauce and water. Cover with a round of waxed paper that fits snugly on the vegetables. Cook the carrots slowly on top of the stove, stirring occasionally, until the carrots are tender and the juices have formed a glaze, 30-40 minutes. Garnish with the mint.

In a large non-stick skillet over medium heat, melt butter and olive oil together. Add the remaining ingredients to the skillet. Stir until potatoes are evenly coated with spice mixture and onion slices are evenly distributed. Cook covered on medium heat for 15 minutes, tossing and turning the potatoes every few minutes. Potatoes will be done when slightly browned and fork-tender.

Heat oil in a large nonstick frying pan over medium heat. Add jimmy dean sausage and saute for about 2 minutes, just until a little browned. Remove sausage and place on a paper towel. Meanwhile, whisk together eggs, milk and baking powder. When sausage is removed from pan, add egg mixture. Sprinkle with sausage and spinach. Top with grated cheese. Cover pan with lid and turn heat down to medium-low. Check after about 3 minutes and see if omelette has set - the middle should not jiggle. Add salt and pepper to taste.

Place tea bags in a large heat-proof measuring cup or pitcher. Pour boiling water over tea bags. Steep 1 hour, or until cooled to room temperature. Remove and discard tea bags. Add pomegranate juice and splenda, stirring until it dissolves. Serve over ice. Garnish with mint sprigs. Makes 4, 1 cup servings.

In a skillet, heat butter or oil. Add in onions. Fry over medium heat until they are soft and golden brown. Remove fries from oven and place half on each slice of toast. Place 1 slice on each of 2 plates. Ladle cup gravy over each serving, top each with half the fried onions, and serve immediately.

In a large pot of boiling water, cook the asparagus until just tender but still bright green drain and rinse with cold water to stop the cooking process. Pat dry with paper towels. While asparagus is cooking, combine the yogurt, mayonnaise, lemon juice, tomatoes, salt and fresh ground pepper. Place the asparagus on a flat plate and spoon the sauce across the center. Serve at room temperature.

In a large mixing bowl, cream the butter until smooth. Add in the sugars. Beat on low for 2 minutes. Add in the milk, syrup, and vanilla. Beat 3-5 minutes until smooth and creamy. Use immediately or store, covered, at room temperature for up to 2 days. Reportedly, the icing tastes better if made the day before because the brown sugar gives the icing a slightly grainy texture that improves if allowed to set overnight.

In a large saucepan over medium low heat, melt 3 tbls butter. Stir flour and salt into pan until creamed together. Slowly stir in cream, then stir in cream cheese, increase heat to medium. Constantly whisk until mixture becomes thick and smooth, remove from heat and set aside. In a large saucepan over medium-high heat, saute onions and garlic in remaining butter until transparent. Add spinach and water to pan, reduce heat to low, cover. Cook, stirring occasionally for 8 minutes. Stir prepared sauce and parmesan cheese into pan, stir until completely blended.

In a small saucepan, stir coffee, milk, granulated sugar, fat free vanilla ice cream, fat free chocolate syrup. Heat gently, continuing to stirring occasionally just until steaming and foam begins to appear. Pour coffee flavored milk into a tall mug and pour espresso over. Top with whip cream and a dash of pumpkin pie spice.

Bake, uncovered, in a 400 degree oven for 35 minutes or until potatoes are tender, stirring occassionaly. Sprinkle with cheese. Bake 5 minutes longer or until cheese is melted. Let stand 5 minutes before serving.

Preheat oven to 325 degrees f. In 2 pans place tomato halves cut side up. Sprinkle with oil, salt and pepper, onion, garlic, oregano, thyme, red wine. Bake tomatoes for 2 hours. Check the tomatoes after 1 hour and turn down the heat if they seem to be cooking too quickly. Then turn the oven to 400 degrees and bake another 30 minutes. Remove from the oven and process tomatoes through a food mill using a medium dye over a small saucepan. Discard skins. Add wine, bring to a boil, reduce heat to low and cook for 5 minutes.
Place salmon on a broiler pan coated with cooking spray. Broil for 8 minute or until salmon flakes easily when tested with a fork.

Preheat oven to 425 degrees f. And grease a 8 inch square baking pan. Sift the sweetbreads together. In a seperate bowl mix the egg, buttermilk oil and honey. Add the egg mixture to the dry ingredients. Beat until smooth. Pour into pan. Bake 20 minutes edges may start to brown a little.

Combine all ingredients except pork chops and rice in a slow cooker. Stir until well blended. Add pork chops. Cook for 6 hours. Serve over rice, or add cooked rice to mixture during the last half hour of cooking.

Mix all ingredients together, except for 2 handfuls of cheese. Pour into a greased casserole dish. Sprinkle remaining cheese on top. Bake at 350 for 40 minutes or so. Recipe can easily be doubled, tripled, etc., but, if using a deep dish, allow extra baking time.

Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Mix the first six ingredients for crust. Place half of mix in a greased 9x13 inch pan. Bake crust for 10 minutes. Melt caramels and whipping cream. Place chocolate chips over baked crust, drizzel caramel over chips, then place the remaining crust mixture on top of the caramel. Bake another 10-15 minutes at 350 degrees. Cool.

Preheat oven to 400f. Place saltine crackers in pan in rows. I usually can fit about 24 in the pan. In a saucepan, bring the butter and sugar to a boil. After it begins boiling, boil for 3 minutes. Immediately pour the butter-sugar mixture on the crackers. Bake in the oven for 7 minutes. Take out of the oven, pour chocolate chips over crackers, and smooth them out after they melt. Cool in the fridge until the chocolate has hardened. Cut into squares.

Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Grease 16 muffin cups. Cut each grandmothers famous cranberry bread in half crosswise to create 2 short round rolls. Press each half roll into one muffin cup, forming it into a cup shape. Mix together ther blueberries, preserves and lemon peel, and spoon some of the mixture into each muffin cup. Sprinkle each cup with pecans. Bake 12 minutes at 375 degrees until golden brown. Cool for 10 minutes in the muffin tin, then remove and place on wire rack. Drizzle icing over rolls. Cool for 10 minutes in the muffin tin

Preheat oven to 350c line base and sides of a 10. 5cm by 21 cm loaf pan with baking paper. Sift flour and cinnamon together into a large bowl. Add sugar and mix. Combine eggs, essence and cooled melted margarine, and stir into dry ingredients until just combined. Fold in apples and sultanas. Spoon mixture into prepared pan and smooth surface. Bake for approximately 55 mins or until a skewer inserted in the centre comes out clean. Allow to cool for 10 mins in pan, then turn out to wire rack to cool completely.
Heat oven to 350 degrees F. Line a baking sheet with parchment paper. Bake asparagus until golden brown, about 10 minutes. Remove from oven and set aside.

In medium size saucepan over medium-high heat combine soy milk with sugar, vanilla, and cinnamon bring to a boil while constantly stirring. In a separate bowl large enough to accommodate the hot liquid beat the egg with a whisk while slowly adding the hot liquid a little bit at a time until all of the liquid has been added to the egg. Place the 2 cups of cooked rice into the pan used to cook the soy milk mixture. Add the soy milk mixture to the rice in the pan and return heat to medium-high, stir constantly until the mixture comes to a boil then reduce heat to simmer. Simmer mixture for 15-20 minutes, stirring every 5 minutes until the mixture is a creamy consistency. Remove from heat, cover top with wax paper and place in the refrigerator to cool.

In a large skillet, saute the chicken in oil until no longer pink. Stir in the soup, water, salt and pepper. Bring to a boil. Remove from heat and stin in sour cream. Serve over toasted english muffins. Can also serve over cooked noodles. Sprinkle with cayenne pepper or paprika.

Place pork on broiler pan coated with cooking spray. Insert a meat thermometer in the thickest part. Bake at 425 degrees for about 25-35 minutes, or until the thermometer registers 160 degrees. Let stand 5 minutes before slicing. Serve with mango chutney.

Heat oil in a large non-stick skillet over medium-high heat. Add chicken, and sprinkle with pepper flakes. Stir fry 3 minutes. Add vegetables and teriyaki sauce. Stir fry 5 minutes or until vegetables are crisp-tender and chicken is thoroughly cooked.

Preheat oven to 325f place apple halves cut-side up in 2 large baking dishes. Spoon 1 teaspoon jam in center of each apple half. Top with goat cheese rounds, and lightly drizzle with oil. Bake pears 30 minutes, or until cheese begins to brown. Whisk together remaining 2 tbs. Fig jam, lemon juice, and mustard in bowl. Whisk in 1 tbs. Olive oil. Divide watercress among 8 serving plates. Sprinkle with onion and walnuts. Top each with apple half, and drizzle with dressing.

Place the butter in a mixing bowl. Add basil, garlic, and cheese and whip with an electric mixer until mixture is smooth and evenly blended. Add salt to taste. Pack butter into four crocks. Allow flavors to blend for at least 4 hours before serving. Can be frozen for up to 3 months.

Stir in the grated carrots. Garnish with fresh herbs and use as a dip for veggies or pita bread. You may also like to add some garlic or a bit of salt, depending on your taste.

Combine all of the ingredients for the sauce in a small bowl. Brush over the chicken. Broil the chicken for 10 minutes each side, 2 inches or so from the heat. Brush frequently with the sauce. Serves 1-2 people.

Place watermelon slices in heavy duty zip lock bag. Seal and freeze for 2 hours. Rub the rim of a cocktail glass with lemon wedge. Place the salt in a saucer and spin the rim of each glass in the salt and set aside. Process the frozen watermelon, tequila, and next 3 ingredients in blender until smooth, stopping to scrape down the sides. Add the ice and blend well, pour into glasses and garnish if desired.

Preheat oven to 325f and spray a baking sheet with pam cooking spray. Put all the dry ingredients into a ziplock bag and shake to combine. Remove chicken from the ziplock bag and shake off any excess buttermilk and add to the breadcrumb mix, add 3 pieces at a time and shake to coat the chicken. Remove and place on baking sheet. Repeat till all pieces are coated. Spray chicken with pam cooking spray and bake for about 20 minutes.

Preheat oven to 350 degrees. After browning and crumbling the breakfast sausage, place it in the bottom of a 9x13 baking dish. Beat eggs, add cheese and salsa verde. Pour egg mixture over the sausage. Bake for 45 minutes or until eggs are set.

Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease a large cookie sheet. Beat butter and sugar in a large bowl with mixer at high speed, until light and fluffy. Add egg and vanilla. Beat until well blended. Combine flour, cocoa, cream of tartar, baking soda and salt in a medium bowl. Add to butter mixture. Mix until uniform. Mix in chopped cherries. Drop dough by tablespoonfuls onto prepared cookie sheet. Bake about 10-12 minutes or until set.

Heat oil over medium heat. Saut garlic until soft, being careful not to let it burn. Add sliced mushrooms and saut until they look fairly cooked and shiny. Add almonds and saut for a couple more minutes. Finally, add frozen green beans and splash of soy sauce. Stir frequently until beans are just cooked and, of course, no longer frozen. If not on the south beach diet or watching sugar intake, you could add oyster sauce or other asian condiment to the mixture.

Preheat the oven to 400f. In a shallow baking pan, arrange the beef sandwiches so they do not touch each other. Bake for 30 minutes. In small sauce pan combine the tomato sauce, sugar and soy sauce and cook until the sugar has dissolved. After the beef sandwiches are cooked, thickly spread the sauce over the beef sandwiches and bake for 30 to 40 minutes or longer or until browned and very tender. Serve warm.
Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Mix ingredients together in a large bowl until well-blended. Roll almond mixture into tablespoon size balls. Bake 12 minutes for chewy cookies. Bake 15 minutes for crisp.

Preheat oven to 325 degrees f. In 2 pans place tomato halves cut side up. Sprinkle with oil, salt and pepper, onion, garlic, and herbs. Bake tomatoes for 2 hours. Check the tomatoes after 1 hour and turn down the heat if they seem to be cooking too quickly. Then turn the oven to 400 degrees and bake another 30 minutes. Remove from the oven and process tomatoes through a food mill using a medium dye over a small saucepan. Discard skins. Add wine, bring to a boil, reduce heat to low and cook for 5 minutes.

Combine marinated artichokes, tomatoes, red bell pepper, parsley, capers, lemons, rind of, lemon juice, sugar, salt and pepper. Set aside. Mix seasonings in small bowl. Coat chicken evenly with the spice rub. Refrigerate 30 minutes or up to 3 hours for extra flavor. Grill over medium heat 25 to 30 minutes or until desired doneness, turning occasionally. Let chicken stand 5 minutes before cutting into thin slices. Test kitchen.

Preheat oven to 400f. Place fish in single layer in baking dish. In nonstick skillet, melt margarine, then saut apple, raisins, nuts, splenda and cinnamon for 3 minutes or until apples are tender. Mix flour with apple juice until dissolved. Add to pan and cook until thickened, stirring constantly, 2 or 3 minutes. Pour sauce over fish. Cover and bake 15 - 20 minutes. Fish should flake easily when tested with fork.

Preheat oven to 325f. Combine cream cheese, sugar and eggs in a small bowl. Beat until fluffy. Place crust on baking sheet. Pour mixture into crust. Bake 25 to 30 minutes. Remove from oven. Cool. Spread low calorie cheesecake on top. Garnish with whipped topping. Chill 3 hours.

Combine everything in a small bowl that can be put in the oven or toaster oven. Stir together until fairly smooth. Place in the oven at 350 degrees for 30 minutes until edges are brown. Let cool for 30 minutes and serve with triscuits. Best served warm.

Preheat oven to 350 degrees f. For the filling, beat cream cheese on medium speed until fluffy. Beat in sugar until blended, then beat in eggs until blended. Stir in white chocolate, cranberries, zest & vanilla. Pour into prepared crust & bake 45-50 minutes or until center is almost set. Cool in pan for 30 minutes, then refrigerate. Run knife around sides of pan to loosen, then chill 4 hours or more. Remove rim & cut into wedges. Refrigerate leftovers.
Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Bake at 350 for 30 minutes or until the cheese is melted.

Heat oil in 2-quart saucepan. Add onion and garlic. Cook over medium heat for about 5 minutes, until onion wilts. Stir in cumin and pepper. Continue to cook for 2-3 minutes. Add oregano, potatoes, green chilies and chicken broth. Bring to a boil and simmer slowly for 45 minutes. Serve hot with cheese sprinkled in the middle of bowl.

Cook red cabbage in large pot of salted water. In another pan, boil eggs. When both have been cooked through, drain and let cool. Peel eggs and chop. In large mixing bowl add cooled potatoes, chopped egg, onion, pickles, and celery seed, salt and pepper. Add sour cream and mayonnaise and stir gently to combine being careful not to mash potatoes. Refrigerate until completely cooled before serving or overnight.

Preheat oven to 400f. Peel, core and slice apples into a bowl. Add brown sugar, cinnamon, water and salt. Mix well to coat apples. Place in two ramikins or small au gratin dishes, sprayed with cooking spray. Dot with butter and spread cheese over top. Bake for 20 to 30 minutes or until apples fall.

Heat oil in 2-quart saucepan. Add onion and garlic. Cook over medium heat for about 5 minutes, until onion wilts. Stir in cumin and pepper. Continue to cook for 2-3 minutes. Add oregano, potatoes, green chilies and chicken broth. Bring to a boil and simmer slowly for 45 minutes. Serve hot with cheese sprinkled in the middle of bowl.

In a saucepan over medium low heat, melt 3 tbls butter. Stir flour and salt into pan until creamed together. Slowly stir in cream, then stir in cream cheese, increase heat to medium. Constantly whisk until mixture becomes thick and smooth, remove from heat and set aside. In a saucepan over medium-high heat, saute onions and garlic in remaining butter until transparent. Add spinach and water to pan, reduce heat to low, cover. Cook, stirring occasionally for 8 minutes. Stir prepared sauce and parmesan cheese into pan, stir until completely blended.

Preheat grill to medium high heat. Create a large aluminum foil packet for each fish fillet. Place salmon in center of foil. Season with garlic salt and brown sugar. Add pieces of butter, then onions. Carefully, pour some beer into foil packet and seal tightly. Grill for 8-10 minutes.

Heat oven to 400f. Put the chicken skin-side-up in a small roasting tin. Mix together the garlic, thyme and butter and dot over the chicken. Scatter around the red onions and pancetta and drizzle with oil. Roast for 20 minutes until the chicken has cooked through and the onions are softened. Divide the salad between 4 plates and top with the red onions, pancetta and chicken.

Remove from heat and add sour cream. Spoon mixture into pasta shell. Add cheese to top and bake 15 minutes.

Preheat oven to 450 degrees f or grill to medium-high. Sprinkle both sides of steak with garlic powder and pepper. Cut in thin strips. Combine steak strips and pepper strips with teriyaki sauce. Center one-fourth of the steak mixture on each sheet of foil. Bring up foil sides. Double fold top and ends to seal packet, leaving room for heat circulation inside. Repeat to make four packets. Bake 12 to 15 minutes on a cookie sheet in oven or grill 7 to 9 minutes in covered grill. Serve immediately over rice. Makes 4 servings.

In small saucepan, stir together maple syrup, brown sugar, butter, half-and-half cream, vanilla extract, walnuts, parmesan cheese, salt and pepper. In a large bowl, combine the salad with lemonade honey dressing. Add enough dressing to coat and toss well. Sprinkle with almonds and serve.

Reduce speed to low, add salt, vanilla, and eggs. Beat until well mixed, about 1 minute. Add flour mixture, mix until just combined. Stir in chocolate chips. Drop heaping spoonfuls about 2 inches apart onto baking trays lined with parchment paper. Bake until golden around the edges and soft in the middle, about 8-10 minutes.

Heat oil to 325 in a deep fryer or a large deep pot, no more than half full. Slice potatoes into wedges. Fry potatoes for 2 minutes and drain, allow to cool off. Turn oil up to 360. Crumble when cooled. Whisk oil, vinegar, mustard, remaining salt, and pepper in a large bowl. Toss with the potatoes, bacon and parsley.

Pour the butter mixture over, tossing to coat, stir in chopped almonds. Enjoy.

Preheat oven to 425 degrees. In a large saucepan over medium heat, melt the butter. Add eggs, icing sugar, kirsch, anise seed, salt, plain flour. Heat to boiling. Pour into a 1. 5 liter casserole. Top with uncooked biscuits. Bake at 425 8-10 minutes or until the biscuits are done.

Preheat oven to 425 degrees f. And grease a 8 inch square baking pan. Sift the cornmeal, flour, baking powder and salt together. In a seperate bowl mix the egg, buttermilk oil and honey. Add the egg mixture to the dry ingredients. Beat until smooth. Pour into pan. Bake 20 minutes edges may start to brown a little.

Preheat oven to 350 degrees farenheit. Mix flour, brown sugar, cocoa, baking soda, and salt with fork together. Mix in remaining ingredients except chocolate chips and pour into an ungreased 8x8x2-inch baking pan. Sprinkle chocolate chips over batter. Bake until wooden pick inserted in center comes out clean, 35-40 minutes. Sprinkle with powdered sugar if desired.

Preheat oven to 375f. Heat a little oil in frying pan and brown stew meat along with onions and carrots. Remove from pan. Layer sliced potatoes, onion, carrot and meat in a 3 pint casserole, finishing with a layer of potatoes. Pour over the stock. Brush the potatoes with 1 tbsp melted butter. Cover and bake for 1 hour. Remove the hot pot from the oven. Uncover and brush the potatoes again with melted butter or dripping. Return to the oven for a further 30 minutes, uncovered, to brown the potatoes. Serve garnished with parsley.

Preheat oven to 325 degrees f. In 2 pans place veal halves cut side up. Sprinkle with oil, salt and pepper, onion, garlic, oregano, thyme, red wine, parsley. Bake tomatoes for 2 hours. Check the tomatoes after 1 hour and turn down the heat if they seem to be cooking too quickly. Then turn the oven to 400 degrees and bake another 30 minutes. Remove from the oven and process tomatoes through a food mill using a medium dye over a small saucepan. Discard skins. Add wine, bring to a boil, reduce heat to low and cook for 5 minutes. Remove from the oven and process tomatoes through a food mill using a medium dye over a

Heat oil over medium heat. Saut garlic until soft, being careful not to let it burn. Add sliced mushrooms and saut until they look fairly cooked and shiny. Add almonds and saut for a couple more minutes. Finally, add frozen green beans and splash of soy sauce. Stir frequently until beans are just cooked and, of course, no longer frozen. If not on the south beach diet or watching sugar intake, you could add oyster sauce or other asian condiment to the mixture.

Heat oven to 425. Heat 1 inch water to boiling in 2-quart saucepan. Add broccoli. Heat to boiling. Reduce heat to medium. Cover and cook about 5 minutes or until crisp-tender. Drain. Mix broccoli, rice, broth, soup, pimientos and pepper in 2-quart casserole. Cover and bake 20 minutes. Cut margarine into baking mix, using pastry blender, until crumbly. Sprinkle crumbly mixture over broccoli mixture. Bake uncovered 8 to 10 minutes or until top is light brown.

In a large bowl, combine all ingredients. Beat with electric mixer until light and very fluffy. Turn into 1 quart casserole dish. Bake at 350 degrees f. In the oven for 20 minutes or until puffed and lightly browned.

Heat oil in a 10-inch skillet over medium-high heat. Cook broccoli, onion, garlic and carrot in oil about 10 minutes, stirring occasionally, until broccoli is crisp- tender. Stir in chicken, salt, and tomatoes. Cook about 3 minutes, stirring occasionally, just until broccoli is hot. Toss with pasta. Sprinkle with cheese and parsley.

Preheat the oven to 350f butter a medium-size gratin dish. Make a layer of one-third of the potato slices in the bottom of the prepared gratin dish. Add a layer of half the onions and then half the carrots. Dot with 2 tablespoons of the butter and season well with salt and pepper. Repeat the layers and finish with the remaining one-third of the potato slices. Dot with the remaining 2 tablespoons of butter and season with salt and pepper. Pour in the stock. Cover with aluminum foil and bake until the vegetables are tender, about 45 minutes. Uncover and sprinkle with the cheese. Bake 10 minutes longer, until the cheese is golden brown. Serve very hot. Makes 6 to 8 servings.

Combine the first 5 ingredients in a large zip-top plastic bag. Seal and marinate in refrigerator 1 hour, turning twice. Remove vegetables from bag, discarding marinade. Preheat oven to 500. Place vegetables in a shallow roasting pan coated with cooking spray. Drizzle with oil, and toss to coat. Sprinkle with salt and pepper. Bake at 500 for 30 minutes or until the vegetables are tender, stirring often.

Heat oil in a large non-stick skillet over medium-high heat. Add chicken, and sprinkle with pepper flakes. Stir fry 3 minutes. Add vegetables and teriyaki sauce. Stir fry 5 minutes or until vegetables are crisp-tender and chicken is thoroughly cooked.

Preheat oven to 350f. Mix salt, meat, egg, and torn up bread together. Fill each muffin cup of muffin pan almost to the top. Top with a onion ring and ketchup in the middle of the ring. Place in oven until thoroughly cooked, about 20-30 minutes.

Briefly heat oil in large, deep pot over medium-high heat. Add beef and onion. Cook, stirring frequently, for 5 minutes. Add garlic, mushrooms and carrots. Cook another 5 minutes. Add pilaf mix, orange juice and beef broth. Bring to a boil, then reduce heat and simmer, covered, for 20 minutes or until liquid has been absorbed.
Preheat oven to 350 degrees F.

Combine all of the ingredients for the sauce in a small bowl. Brush over the chicken. Broil the chicken for 10 minutes each side, 2 inches or so from the heat. Brush frequently with the sauce. Serves 1-2 people.

Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Bake in preheated 350 degree oven for 20-25 minutes. Cool in pans on wire racks for 10 minutes, then remove from pan and let cool completely. Frost cupcakes with vanilla frosting, and garnish each one with a reserved cherry.
Place bacon and tomato on top of grilled cheese sandwich. Place bacon and tomato on top of grilled cheese sandwich. Place bacon and tomato on top

Combine all of the ingredients, except the rhubarb, together in a blender. Cover and blend on low speed for 3 minutes. Pour into a greased 9-inch pie pan. Let stand about 5 minutes then sprinkle with rhubarb. Bake at 350 degrees for 40 minutes. Serve warm or cool.
Preheat oven to 350f. In medium bowl, combine cream of chicken soup, whole kernel corn, cooked chicken, cream of mushroom soup, thyme, pie crustpreparation:Preheat oven to 350f.

Heat oil in a 10-inch skillet over medium heat. Cook broccoli, onion, garlic and carrot in oil about 10 minutes, stirring occasionally, until broccoli is crisp- tender. Stir in chicken, salt, and tomatoes. Cook about 3 minutes, stirring occasionally, just until broccoli is hot. Toss with pasta. Sprinkle with cheese and parsley.

Preheat oven to 400. Cover a glass baking dish with aluminum foil and place the chicken breasts on top. Zest all 3 of the lemons into a small bowl, and then add the juice of 2 of the lemons. Add the pepper and all the other ingredients into the bowl. Mix the combine and pour over all the chicken breasts. Bake for 1 hour. Remove from the oven and drizzle with the lemon juice of the last lemon, and a few more grinds from pepper mill.

Heat grill to medium-high heat. Mix mayo and basil. Refrigerate until ready to use. Combine meat and garlic. Shape into 8 thin patties. Top 4 patties with cheese. Cover with remaining patties. Pinch edges together to seal. Grill 7 to 9 minute on each side or until burgers are done. Spread buns with mayo mixture. Fill with lettuce, tomatoes, burgers and peppers.

In a heat proof bowl or pitcher, pour boiling water over tea bags. Cool at least 15 minutes. Add mint and let tea bags steep for at least 5 minutes. Strain. Add lemonade concentrate. Stir well. Refrigerate. Serve with lemon slices and extra mint.

Add water, oil, skim milk powder, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour, white bread flour

Place pork butt, onions, ginger ale, barbecue sauce in a slow cooker. Cover and cook on low for 6-8 hours or high for 4-5 hours or until pork is very tender. Remove pork to a large cutting board or platter and let rest for 10-15 minutes. Remove pork to a large cutting board or platter

Preheat oven to 350f. In a large bowl, combine margarine, brown sugar, granulated sugar, egg, vanilla extract, all-purpose flour, cornstarch, baking soda, chocolate. Add to butter mixture and then add chocolate chunks. Drop by tablespoons onto a greased baking sheet and bake for 8-10 minutes, until golden brown around the edges.
Place beef bouillon cubes in crock pot. Cover and cook on low for 1 hour. Add red wine. Cover and cook on high for 1 hour

In a small mixing bowl, combine sugar and cinnamon. Set aside. In a small microwave pyrex bowl, melt butter in microwave. Take breadsticks and cut them in half lengthwise. Take each halved breadstick and dip into butter then roll in cinnamon mixture. Twist each strip 2 or 3 times and place on ungreased baking sheets. Bake at 350 degrees for 15 to 18 minutes. Let cool on wire racks. Makes 16 toasted sticks.

Cook caesar salad according to directions on package, drain and cool by running cool water over it. Let drain thoroughly. Combine caesar salad with peppers, carrots and parsley. Add vinaigrette and mix well. Add feta cheese, mix lightly, lifting the caesar salad and cheese mixture until the cheese is distributed throughout. Chill for an hour before serving.

Preheat the oven to 375. Place the chicken, with the skins on, in a single layer in a shallow roasting dish and set aside. Heat the oil in a small saucepan and gently fry the green onions and garlic for about 2 minutes, until softened, but not browned. Add the honey, orange juice, orange segments and soy sauce to the pan, stirring well and cook until the honey has completely dissolved. Pour the sauce over the chicken and bake, uncovered, for about 45 minutes, basting once or twice until the chicken is cooked.

Preheat oven to 450 degrees. Grease a 12 cup muffin pan or you can use a mini muffin pan. Combine cornmeal, flour, baking powder and salt in a large bowl. In a separate bowl, combine egg whites, onion, milk, parsley, oil and pepper. Add to dry ingredients stirring just until moistened. Spoon into prepared muffin tins. Bake for 10-12 minutes or until lightly browned. Remove and cool on a rack for 5 minutes. Remove

Add beef eye round, tomato paste, marsala wine, red wine vinegar, warm water, brown sugar, garlic cloves, onion soup mix, thyme, pepper. Cover and cook on low for 2 hours. Add beef eye round, tomato paste, marsala wine, red wine vinegar, warm water, brown sugar, garlic cloves, onion soup mix, thyme, pepper. Add beef eye round, tomato paste, marsala wine, red wine

Preheat oven to 350 degrees c. In a large bowl sift together flour, salt, baking soda, butter, granulated sugar, egg, vanilla extract, all-purpose flour, cornstarch, baking soda, chocolatepreparation:Preheat oven to 350 degrees c. In a large bowl sift together flour, cornstarch and baking soda. Add to butter mixture and then add chocolate chunks. Drop by tablespoons onto a greased baking sheet and bake for 8-10 minutes, until golden brown around the edges.

Preheat oven to 350 degrees farenheit. Cream sugar and margarine. Add bananas and eggs. Sift cake flour, salt, and baking soda 3 times. Blend flour mixture into banana mixture, making sure not to overmix. Turn batter into 2 greased 9x5x3-inch loaf pans. Bake for 55 minutes, or until toothpick inserted in center of loaf comes out clean. Turn out immediately to cool on wire rack.

In a small bowl, mix cream cheese, cream cheese, rotel, smoked sausage, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream cheese, cream

Preheat oven to 350f. Stir together olive oil, garlic, yellow onion, beet leaves, white wine, bacon bits, salt, fresh ground black pepper in a 6-quart dutch oven over medium heat for 1 to 2 minutes or until garlic is light brown. Add spinach. Toss well to coat. Cook and stir 2 minutes more or just until spinach is wilted and heated through. To serve, sprinkle with parmesan cheese.

Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Mix the first six ingredients for crust. Place half of mix in a greased 9x13 inch pan. Bake crust for 10 minutes. Melt caramels and whipping cream. Place chocolate chips over baked crust, drizzel caramel over chips, then place the remaining crust mixture on top of the caramel. Bake another 10-15 minutes at 350 degrees. Cool.

Preheat the oven to 375. Place the chicken, with the skins on, in a single layer in a shallow roasting dish and set aside. Heat the oil in a small saucepan and gently fry the green onions and garlic for about 2 minutes, until softened, but not browned. Add the honey, orange segments and soy sauce to the pan, stirring well and cook until the honey has completely dissolved. Pour the sauce over the chicken and bake, uncovered, for about 45 minutes, basting once or twice until the chicken is cooked.

Heat the oil over medium-high heat. Add the cherry tomatoes and cook, tossing and stirring often, until the skins begin to split, about 3 minutes. Do not over cook. Remove from the heat and toss with the herbs. Season with salt and pepper. Serve immediately. Makes 4-6 servings.

Preheat oven to 350. Melt butter or margarine. Stir in brown sugar until dissolved. Stir oatmeal and cereal into butter and sugar. Stir in chocolate chips and skor bits, or any other tasty fillers you would like. Line a cookie sheet with parchment paper. Pack oatmeal mix into cookie sheet. Bake in oven for 10 minutes. Cool, and cut into 24 pieces.

Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Mix together flour, eggs, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine, margarine
Place the blueberries in a large bowl and mix well. Add sugar and mix well. Bake for 1 hour. At 350 degrees.

Preheat the oven to 375f. Butter a round, 2-quart baking dish and pour in the fruit. Mix the farina, sugar, baking powder and salt together in a medium bowl. Beat the egg with the vanilla and add it to the farina mixture. Mix well with a fork or finger. Sprinkle the topping evenly over the fruit and pour the butter evenly over it. Bake for 30 to 35 minutes or until the top is lightly brown. Serve warm or at room temperature.

Heat 3 tsp of oil in a skillet or a stir fry pan. Add cabbage and stir fry cabbage for about 2 minutes or until tender. Remove cabbage and keep warm. Sprinkle with salt and pepper, to taste. In the same pan, add 3 tsp of oil and stir fry onions and garlic until tender. Add the shrimp, water and soy sauce. Cook until shrimp turns pink. Sprinkle with cilantro and red pepper flakes, stir. Serve shrimp mixture over cabbage.

Cook marinade for meat ala chipotle in a large saucepan over medium heat, stirring occasionally, until the meat is browned, 8 to 10 minutes. Add garlic, chili powder, cumin and cayenne. Cook until fragrant, about 15 seconds. Stir in salsa and water. Bring to a simmer. Reduce heat to medium-low, cover and cook, stirring occasionally, until the vegetables are tender, 10 to 15 minutes. Stir in beans and cook until heated through, about 1 minute.
Combine romaine lettuce hearts, baby spinach, hearts of palm, cucumber, carrot, tomatoes, red onion, frozen green pea, capers. Add spinach and toss. Add

Heat carrot soup to boiling and add extra virgin olive oil and fresh ginger. Simmer for 10 minutes, stirring occasionally, until vegetables are tender. Return to pot. Add onion and ginger and stir for 10 minutes. Simmer for 10 minutes.

Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Lightly grease a 12 cup muffin pan. In a medium saucepan with enough water to cover, boil squash 20 minutes, or until tender. Remove from heat, drain, and puree in a food processor. In a large bowl, thoroughly mix together flour, baking powder, sugar, salt and pumpkin pie spice. In a medium bowl, thoroughly mix together milk, egg and applesauce. Stir in squash. Fold the squash mixture into the flour mixture just until moistened. Spoon batter into the greased muffin pan, filling cups about full. Bake 20 minutes.

Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Brown beef and onions in skillet. Drain. Mix in tomato sauce, garlic and oregano. Place in a 2-quart casserole dish. Top with corn. Then spread mashed potatoes over the corn. Lay cheese over the mashed potatoes in a single layer. Bake for about 25-30 minutes or until the cheese is completely melted.

Preheat oven to 350f. Season chicken breasts with garlic powder, salt and pepper. Wrap each chicken breast in 1 strip of bacon and place in a 9x13x2-inch baking dish. In a small bowl, mix the sour cream and soup. Spoon mixture over the chicken and bake uncovered for 40 to 50 minutes or until slightly brown on top. Serve with hot cooked rice, if desired.

Melt butter in a large skillet. Add rice and stir, about 2 minutes, making sure grains are nicely coated with butter. Add lemon zest, pepper, and the broth. Simmer uncovered over low heat for about 40 minutes, or until the liquid has absorbed and rice in tender. Remove from heat. Add lemon juice and stir. Let stand 5 minutes. Garnish with lemon slices to serve.

Place all ingredients except cheese in crockpot and cook on low for 6 hours. Use two forks to shred the beef into chunks. Add cheese and stir. Serve immediately in tacos or use as a filling for enchiladas. You can also use chicken breasts, but it turns out drier and not as tasty.

Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Grease 8x8 square pan. Melt butter and cool slightly and add milk and beaten egg, set to the side. In bowl, sift the next four ingredients, 2 times. Add butter, milk, and egg mixture and stir only enough to smooth out any lumps. Combine the remaining sugar and cinnamon for the topping, in a small bowl or in a ziploc bag. Pour batter into greased pan and sprinkle the mixture of sugar and cinnamon over the top and bake 12 to 15 minutes.

Rinse mushrooms, pat dry with paper towel. Heat oil in a medium pan, saute garlic until fragrant. Add mushrooms, stir quickly then season with salt, pepper, sugar and soy sauce. Saute until some liquid starts to evaporate. Remove from heat, spoon into serving dish and garnish with cilantro.

Heat olive oil in large skillet over medium heat. Add garlic, onion and garlic, and saute for 2-3 minutes, or until vegetables are tender. Add chicken broth, tomatoes, oregano, basil and black pepper. Bring to a boil and cook for 2 minutes. Reduce heat to medium-low. Place linguine fillets in the sauce, cover, and simmer for 7-9 minutes, or until the fish flakes easily with a fork. Individual fillets with sauce may be served over a bed of cooked rice.
